Bug.WithStack:
In the following code, Klass.CONSTANT is available as an autocompletion by
typing "Klass." and pressing Ctrl-Space:

  Vector<String> list = x.getVect(Klass.CONSTANT);

However, there are no autocompletions available in the corresponding position of
the following:

  for (String str : x.getVect(Klass.CONSTANT))

Interestingly though, "x." provides "x.getVect" as an autocompletion in the
second example, but "x.getVect(Klass.C" yields no autocompletions.

The enhanced for-loop syntax seems to be interfering with autocompletion.
3.1M7.

Tom, please comment
core problem - we don't get any proposals here. Snippet to reproduce (caret at |):


-------- Tester.java --------------
package com.example;

import java.util.Vector;

public class Tester {
	
	private static final int CONSTANT= 42;
	
	Vector<String> getVect(int x) {
		return null;
	}
	
	void foo(Tester x) {
		for (String str: x.getVect(Tester.C|)) {
			
		}
	}
}
-------- 

Note: there is no code assist within the 'getVect' argument list at all -
neither type nor constant completion.
The problem doesn't exist anymore in N20050607-0010

